description.text:
I wanted a big volume knob to suit my big power amp. Couldn't find any in the right size, let alone the style I wanted.
I want to backlight my volume knob so that light shines across the panel from behind it. this requires a particular structure in the back of the knob.
3D printer to the rescue!

Vertical section should be sliced with 0.2mm layer height, and the dome should be done at 0.05mm layer height (yes 50 microns, that's not a typo). Since very thin layers don't print well with sparse infill, we splice on the solid layers just above the bridge. The STL is suited for a 1/4" D shaft although it should be pretty easy to change this for any shaft type. After printing, cut off the wings that help prevent the center colum from warping, and paint the back of the knob white to assist reflections from the backlighting. See http://github.com/triffid/Volume-Knob for latest files including a Makefile to automagically do the splicing for you

comments.text: Depends on how carefully you balance the rotor and fit its bearing points.  If spun-up by wrapping a string around the axle and pulling quickly it will spin for about 30 seconds if well fitted. I printed mine at 200% (Red) and the base stands at 56 mm tall. You can also print at 150% (Grey) which stands at 42 mm. Fully customizable and modular, look for more designs to come in the following weeks.

Made in Tinkercad, red printed at my library, grey printed on my Monoprice MP Select Mini
The remixed and improved version of my 2014 work that was unprintable and abandoned shortly after inception

note
The shield comes in four variety's, one of which is included here. Find more embossed shields and chest appliances here --> http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2073640

Printing
The pieces should be printed at 150-200% depending on what you feel your printers accuracy to be. My printer can make all the details clearly visible at 100% but needs the print to be at 150% in order to fit together well.
The picture shows the 3 sizes of 200%, 150%, and 100%

Preparation
In order for the pieces to properly fit together, you will need to lightly sand them with a set of needle files. The heads just need very minute sanding in the eye holes. My first layer is always slightly off which always needs work in that one spot. The studs that attach to the shirt and pants need light sanding, but the holes should be fine, depending on your printers accuracy. The shirt stud typically needs a very small amount of sanding compared to the pant studs. The bottom that fits onto the base will most likely need sanding on both the hole and stud depending on accuracy.

Always test fit pieces together as you sand. I'm not responsible for ruined pieces due to too much sanding.

This was a student project for Valentine's Day. The students designed a heart shaped box with a customized lid.

Because the box bottoms will all be the same you can print them ahead to save time.

If you print the boxes at 150%, 100%, and 50% they will nest inside each other.

Posted here is a blank box and lid you can customize, and one with a bow and the name "Ali" I made as a test for my niece. I also made a box top with a real heart on it. The other box tops are student designs.

Here's a link to the blank bank and top on Tinkercad: https://www.tinkercad.com/things/3yAB57h1Ssj-heart-shaped-box/editv2

I printed the lid face up, despite the overhang. This create a somewhat hairy underside but it's concealed, and the top wasn't affected. If this is a concern you can print it with support. With the lid face up there isn't much surface in contact with the build plate. I didn't have any trouble printing in, but you might need a brim so it sticks.
NGSS

This is an art / 3D design project for middle school students. The students designed a heart shaped box as a Valentine's Day gift for someone and customized the top. Could also work for other occasions, like Mother's Day. Since all the box bottoms will be the same you can print them in advance and save time. You can make the project easier by giving the students the blank box top to start with. Here's a link to the box and box top on tinkercad: https://www.tinkercad.com/things/3yAB57h1Ssj-heart-shaped-box/editv2 A common mistake made by students doing this project is rotating the lid not quite 180 degrees. This will cause problems when printing, so watch out for it.

Making the Bottom of the box
  • Start a new design on Tinkercad
  • Drag a heart shape onto the work plane
  • Change the dimensions of the heart to 100 mm x 100 mm and a height of 40 mm
  • Duplicate the heart and make the duplicate a hole
  • Change the dimension of the heart shaped hole to 92 mm x 92 mm and lift it 2 mm above the work plane
  • Use Align to center the heart shaped hole and heart
  • Group the heart and heart shaped hole and check that you have a box with solid walls, correct if necessary
    • Making the Lid
  • Drag a heart shape onto the work plane
  • Change the dimensions of the heart to 110 mm x 110 mm and a height of 14 mm
  • Duplicate the heart and make the duplicate a hole
  • Change the dimension of the heart shaped hole to 101.2 mm x 101.2 mm and a height of 12 mm
  • Use Align to center the heart shaped hole and heart
  • Group the heart and heart shaped hole and check that you have a lid with solid walls, correct if necessary
  • Customize the lid, you can shapes, pictures, a name, etc.
  • Print your box and lid
  • Optional - you can decorate with paint, markers, glitter etc.
None, unless you plan to have the students paint or decorate their box. Or want to provide or make gifts to go inside the box.

comments.text: FWIW, (assuming my memory is correct) the engines for the World War II "Liberty" ships were triple expansion steam, of around 750 HP.  The reason that these were used was that they didn't require really tight tolerance machining, and so could be made in a lot more machine shops (unlike the engines used in WW II military ships, or the "one-off" designs for passenger liners and such at the time).  The triple expansion engines were "reasonably" efficient for their day.  I'd be surprised if you couldn't dig up the blue prints for the Liberty ship engines, though it might take some trying.

description.text:
I wanted a spool holder that would hold a varying size of spools and didn't require any extra hardware other than what came with my printer. Here is what I came up with.

Designed for the standard 8mm threaded rod that came with my A6. Parabolic caps, and a threaded rod makes it adjustable to suit most spools. The threaded rod is designed to "lock" into one cap preventing it from going farther than need be. There are 2 options for the rod: Short stops at the inner threads of the caps on a standard 1kg spool. Long extends to the outer perimeter of the caps flush with the face. I would recommend the "Long".

It has been working very well and thought I would share.

Update Spun the cap off the bolt too fast, hit the floor and broke part of the hub. So we have V2 with no outside ring and I like it a lot more. I also included a bolt for a 10mm rod.

comments.text:
The leadscrews are held at the top only. The other end are free except of course for the nuts bolted to the X carriage. The X carriage hangs from the top bearings then. I don't use ball bearings(most cheap 608 are shitty BTW) but Igus bearings I made.
You could use bronze bearings or even print them with ABS, PLA, Nylon would be better. They are not stressed and the RPM is low so won't wear out.
The leadscrews won't transmit any force in the X/Y plane even if they were slightly bent. The belt tension cancel any play in the bearings too.
The belt can be made or purchased. For the Geetech I designed the parts for a 760mm GT2
The Z smooth rods are there to constrain in the X,Y plane and it is better to replace these shitty SS soft rod supplied in the kits by hardened steel rod (h7 class). Should be done for all the axis unless you replace the linear bearings by Igus ones. They are a major cause of the noise and get damaged quickly (grooves)

title: Slim Rostock Max V3/HE280 Fan Shroud, Light Weight, Rounded
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
BIG UPDATE 11/7/2017:
After many redesigns and tests, I am posting the 5th (and I hope final) version. This shroud fits within the slim enclosure and allows printing to the edge without hitting the bed clips. The autocalibration wizard and OctoPrint plugins run flawlessly. I should really do some bridging tests to see how much this improves bridging, but it does put a bunch of air on the plastic without cooling the nozzle. Also, note the green bowden coupler above the fans; this allows easier filament changes when the tube is tightened into the HE280 hot end. I have included STLs for the coupler and a Tall PTC tool so that you can tighten down the bowden tube without removing the fans. The coupler uses the following fittings: https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B01IB81IHG

I have reprinted all of the parts in the Yellow PETG that you see in image for strength and heat resistance. I think that the fan shroud might be too close to the heater block to use PLA.

Note 3/23/2017:
I recognize that these shrouds cause issues printing at the very edge of the bed due to the bed clips and the enclosure wall. These shrouds currently prevent the 10 point auto-calibration via the SeeMeCNC wizard or the OctoPrint Delta Plugin. I am currently working on a redesign, but am not ready to post. If you wish to run the 10 point auto-calibration, please remove the fan shrouds to prevent crashes.

Update 1/24/2017:
V2 is based on feedback that the shroud exit was too low and was hitting prints. This is designed to give more clearance (1mm from bottom to nozzle exit with the stock nozzle) and to direct the flow below the heater block. I've also slimmed the main duct to reduce chance of arm collision.

Original 1/23/2017:
From Noircogi: "This mod moves the three part fans on the HE280 in and up above the hot end. The point of this mod is to allow a narrow enclosure. The stock part fan layout moves the fans considerably outside the base frame when the head is near the bed limits. This allows full travel with a narrow enclosure.

Airflow is a bit less, but better directed. You still will not need to run the fans at 100% in my experience.

You will need to trim the small plastic tabs on the effector plate before installing the shrouds."

I would also like to credit http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1900098 for inspiring the shape of the end of duct and the wall thickness and for pointers to the hotend models.

My contribution here is to make the part lighter, more rounded, and to improve the direction of the airflow towards the space directly beneath the nozzle. On my hotend, the shroud easily clears the bed/part when using the stock nozzle. This means that with the longer ED3 nozzles, there should be no clearance issues at all.

Update1: I made new crank, its reinforced and its easier to rotate slowly (I made it 3 gearboxes as its relatively hard to rotate whole thing) next step would be to improve planet gears holder as its now weakest part for 3 gearboxes variant.
Update2: I added reinforced version of planets holder thingies, they are pretty solid now and I consider this project finished :) https://youtu.be/ytXheS1m-V4
PS i find 2 gearboxes and old crank as best one, 3 gearboxes are cool but too much friction ruins the fun and also more possibilities for whole system to jam... but the choice is yours :)

How to assemble (sorry for quiet audio) https://youtu.be/9Z3ExSQPsK8

Hello , I just want to publish my few months worth project :) I don`t know why but I wanted to make mechanical toy, something that can do something while few days ago it was just static filament roll.

Straight away I want to thanks those guys
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1415432
and
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:56542
as I used their parts as I felt I will have troubles creating my own fan and my own gears.Thank you for publishing your projects even tho I heavily modified them.

There is no suggestions to how you should print it, just one thing - there is no need in supports in any of parts and there is no crazy business with shapes. Your printer should be pretty accurate for parts like fan case and fan holder and there will be veeery small gap when you insert one into another so it will rotate freely but it wont jump left and right and all over the place. So i hope your printer can do it.
Assembling should be easy
1) insert Fan_case_pin into Fan_case, there is small cap on pin and bit wider hole end in case so pin will stop at the right moment
2) insert Planet_gear into Planet_holder_bottom while keeping the small bump on gear on top
3) close the Planet_holder bottom with Planet_holder_top
4) take Fan_holder and insert it into Fan, there should be click sound when you do so and it should hold fan firmly and without skews
5) insert Fan_holder with Fan into Fan_case with planetary gearbox awaiting on the other end
6) place Crank_holder on top of assembled gearbox
7) insert the Crank_pin into Crank the same way you did with Fan_case pin and Fan_case
8) insert Crank_handle into assembled Crank_pin (take note that this is one way trip, it will hold on in place pretty firmly but pins inside crank handle will break if you try to take it off)
9) insert the assembled Crank into Crank_holder
10) there are Pin and Short_pin, there are not really needed but I made my models ready for them even tho i dont really plan to use them (maybe short pin only)
Short pin is to connect Fan_holder and Planets_holder_top so it wont move up and down at high speeds, Pin is to connect gearbox with gearbox and gearbox with crank buuuut, maybe connecting gearbox with crank can be good idea ,it works without pins.
11) only thing i suggest is to glue gearbox ring gears together with each other and fan case pins with gearbox so it wont fall apart if you will try to use it to its max

Anyway sorry if i forgot something , there were tons and tons of iterations and thinking involved there is like 10 versions of everything but i think its pretty reliable and easy to make now, hope you like it. Enjoy!

Ah almost forgot , main feature of this one is you can place one gearbox after another, multiplying speed more and more! :)

description.text:
Due to the FDM printing process, the inside of the holes always gets smaller than it was designed. For this reason it is interesting to print a reference guide for calibration of the projects that will be created.

The internal dimension of the hole also changes depending on the shape it is printed on, so print twice the same model, horizontally and vertically.

In each of the models, we have six smaller measurements and nine larger ones, which have undergone alteration of 0.10mm. The hole with the correct measure appears has its contour differentiated by two circles.

==================================================================

Devido ao processo de impressão FDM, a parte interna dos furos sempre fica menor do que foi projetado. Por esta razão é interessante imprimir um guia de referencia para calibração dos projetos que serão criados.

A dimensão interna do furo também sofre alteração dependendo da forma que é impressa, portanto, imprima duas vezes o mesmo modelo, na horizontal e vertical.

Em cada um dos modelos, temos seis medidas menores e nove maiores, que sofreram alteração de 0,10mm. O furo com a medida correta tem seu contorno diferenciado por dois circulos.

title: Tevo Black Widow - Heated Bed Wire Strain Relief

description.text:
Add on that allows you to anchor the heated build plate wiring harness to the Y carriage to relieve strain at the connections to the bed. I used a screw and threaded insert to help anchor this piece to my Y carriage. Friction alone might hold this in place, or you could probably use a small amount of adhesive to hold it in place as well.

There are two versions: one is designed for a PEM M3 press-in threaded insert, the other accomplishes the same job with a standard M3 nut. You need an M3 screw in 8-12mm length if you want to use the nut or threaded insert. Just snug the screw -- too much tightening and you'll just break the part.

DISCLAIMER: I just installed this and haven't done any long printing projects to know how well it will stay in place.

UPDATE (7/2017) - I have been using my printer extensively with this in place, and it has been working wonderfully.

CUMULATIVE UPDATE: uploaded ALL my gear 3d files. I've spent a couple of weeks making these! Please remember to LIKE or even better, COMMENT! Thanks!

This contains a Traxxas 46p 76-tooth spur gear (among others and pinions) which I use for my Slash 2WD RC car. It is a high quality and accurately measured 20th generation design which I am currently racing with, and it prints well even on my rudimentary 3d printer. It replaced my 86 tooth stock gear and added about 3-5 mph. I ease into the throttle and loosen the clutch to about half a turn out when using this gear to avoid stripping it. It does make some noise. Any suggestions or requests, please let me know. This was my first 3d object uploaded to this site, so please give me a like!
